@ajayns08 @adarsh_menon_ To an extent it's about how passionate you are about what you do. If you really love what you do, it would take a lot of pain for you to think that what you do is hard. Nothing wrong in encouraging good work ethic, but must come with the caveat of knowing when to let go.

@ajayns08 @adarsh_menon_ Well it's not that it's glorified,just that you will have times in your life where you don't like what you do but have to do it anyway. Then you have to dig in and work hard to complete the task. Maybe it's glorified, but hard work is imp too. Not everyone loves what they do.

@adarsh_menon_ Aah but again, you are speaking with hindsight. Most kids hate the concept of working hard. I used to, and even now I see my younger brother in the same situation. No matter what I tell him about having to work hard, he doesn't want to- coz they want to enjoy life.

@adarsh_menon_ No, that's something that will create a nihilistic attitude in young minds. It's easy for our young minds to switch off and give up easily if we already know things get harder and thus we are fed this idea that things will get better if you work hard as a child.
